This project has been able to demonstrate how we can create UFW firewall policy to 
allow web access (http and https) and block SSH from unknown IPs. 
The project was Implemented using UFW on Ubuntu. 
Use Kali Linux to simulate different network scans and connection attempts. 
Firewalls effectively mitigate unauthorized access and network enumeration by acting 
as a barrier between a network and external sources, carefully filtering and 
controlling network traffic based on predefined security rules. 
By monitoring and inspecting traffic, firewalls can detect and block malicious or 
suspicious activity, preventing unauthorized users from accessing the network and 
enumerating its resources. 
Firewalls analyze network traffic based on rules (e.g., IP addresses, ports, protocols) 
to determine which traffic is allowed and which is blocked. This allows administrators 
to control which sources can connect to specific services or resources within the 
network. 
ACLs within firewalls define specific rules for granting or denying access to network 
resources based on various criteria. 
With stateful Inspection, firewalls is able track the state of active connections and 
make decisions based on the context of the traffic, blocking unwanted communication 
attempts. 
Firewalls can be configured to restrict incoming and outgoing network traffic, reducing 
the attack surface and minimizing the exposure of sensitive information. 
By blocking access to unnecessary ports and protocols, organizations can 
significantly reduce the likelihood of enumeration attempts being successful. 
Firewalls inspects the contents of data packets, enabling them to identify and block 
specific types of traffic, such as malicious code or prohibited file types. 
Firewalls can be integrated with IPS capabilities to detect and block malicious traffic 
associated with enumeration attempts. 
They act as a gatekeeper between the network and external threats, preventing 
unauthorized access. 
This project provided us with valuable hands-on experience in understanding and 
implementing basic firewall security on a Linux system. By designing and applying a 
firewall policy using UFW (or iptables), we learned how to control traffic, allowing only 
trusted connections while blocking potentially harmful or unauthorized access. 
Testing the firewall using Kali Linux tools like Nmap gave us a practical insight into 
how attackers might attempt to scan or exploit open ports. Observing how the firewall 
reacted to these attempts helped reinforce the importance of defensive cybersecurity 
practices. 
One key takeaway is how critical firewall configuration is in the broader context of 
system hardening. Even a simple policy, if correctly implemented, can significantly 
reduce the attack surface of a system. 
Overall, this project has deepened our understanding of: 
Network security fundamentals 
The importance of restricting access based on IP and port 
The practical use of cybersecurity tools and Linux command-line utilities 
We hope that this project shows others how straightforward and powerful basic 
firewall setups can be. It emphasizes the value of preventative security and 
encourages proactive defense strategies in real-world environments.
